{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516110"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:38:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:38:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12563"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12563"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.03,0.75,0.17,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5062"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98021"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5062"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80552"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"478"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8530"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42781"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44591"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98021"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with shortness of breath. He has become increasingly breathless over the past two days, and is now complaining of chest discomfort. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 115/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His heart sounds are muffled and his jugular venous pressure is visible 4 cm above the sternal angle. His chest x-ray is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left lower lobe collapse","Mediastinal mass","Pericardial effusion","Congestive heart failure","Aortic dissection"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical presentation demonstrates 2/3 of Beck\u0027s triad for \u003Cstrong\u003Epericardial effusion\u003C/strong\u003E, which are hypotension, distended neck veins and muffled heart sounds. The chest X-ray demonstrates the water bottle sign. In pericardial effusion, the excess fluid causes the pericardium to sag, creating a shape that resembles an old fashioned water bottle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft lower lobe collapse\u003C/strong\u003E should preserve the heart contours as the collapse would appear superimposed on the cardiac shadow, however this is not seen on the chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Emediastinal mass\u003C/strong\u003E is possible the chest X-ray is much more reasonably explained by a pericardial effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E is a good thought given the symptoms would fit and the heart appears enlarged on the chest X-ray. However given the acuity, patient age, and presence muffled heart sounds, it is more in keeping with a pericardial effusion. In congestive heart failure, there should be pulmonary congestion and Kerly B lines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic dissection\u003C/strong\u003E may present with a widened mediastinum on chest X-ray but this diagnosis would not adequately explain the globular-shaped heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon causes of pericardial effusion include infections (viral, bacterial, tuberculous), malignancy (lung cancer, breast cancer, lymphoma, leukaemia), autoimmune conditions (rheumatoid arthritis, systemic lupus erythematosus), post-myocardial infarction (Dressler syndrome), trauma, uraemia, hypothyroidism, and iatrogenic causes (post-cardiac surgery, radiation therapy). In a previously healthy young adult, viral pericarditis would be a common cause, but further investigation would be needed to determine the specific aetiology in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The water bottle sign on chest x-ray is suggestive of a large pericardial effusion.","Beck\u0027s triad (hypotension, distended neck veins, muffled heart sounds) is indicative of cardiac tamponade, often due to pericardial effusion.","Pericardial effusion can be caused by infection, malignancy, autoimmune conditions, trauma, or metabolic disorders."],"references":["Gaillard F, Param-Phillips P, Carroll D, et al. Pericardial effusion. [Internet].  Reference article, Radiopaedia.org Accessed on 8 Jan 2025. Available from: https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-7729","Stolz L, Valenzuela J, Situ-LaCasse E, Stolz U, Hawbaker N, Thompson M, Adhikari S. Clinical and historical features of emergency department patients with pericardial effusions. World J Emerg Med. 2017;8(1):29-33. doi: 10.5847/wjem.j.1920-8642.2017.01.005. PMID: 28123617; PMCID: PMC5263032. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28123617/","Willner DA, Goyal A, Grigorova Y, Sharma S, Kiel J. Pericardial Effusion. 2024 Jul 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613741. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28613741/","Vakamudi S, Ho N, Cremer PC. Pericardial Effusions: Causes, Diagnosis, and Management. Prog Cardiovasc Dis. 2017 Jan-Feb;59(4):380-388. doi: 10.1016/j.pcad.2016.12.009. Epub 2017 Jan 4. PMID: 28062268. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28062268/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80552"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12563"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19576"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19576"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/36f5f4cd-96d0-45cd-952f-1795a782731c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/36f5f4cd-96d0-45cd-952f-1795a782731c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":537,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80552"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-10T19:08:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-10T19:12:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5062"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98021"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"h